<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="19" pageNumber="358" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1944,2044]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1437,152,1007]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="19" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,1944,1971]" pageId="19" pageNumber="358">Description (</emphasis>
based on 
<typeStatus box="[461,559,1945,1971]" pageId="19" pageNumber="358">holotype</typeStatus>
unless indicated otherwise). Prostomium retracted within segments II and III, more visible in ventral view, with two pairs melded red eyes; notopodia of segment II with six spines (
<figureCitation box="[1284,1422,1981,2008]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="18.[151,250,2018,2043]" captionTargetBox="[183,1404,564,1975]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[174,1414,552,1996]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 10. H. furfuricula sp. nov. Red Sea, Holotype, NTM W.25602. A. anterior end, dorsal view; B. ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442534/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="358">Fig. 10 A, B</figureCitation>
). Barrel-like pharynx with two stylets, posterior caeca present. Mid-body notopodium with lateral spine; main paleae number nine, with (20) 22–24 (25) ribs and 9–10 (12) shallow raised ribs supporting small denticles that loosely line up in rows (
<figureCitation box="[332,439,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1838,1863]" captionTargetBox="[178,1419,386,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,373,1818]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 11. H. furfuricula sp. nov. A–B. Inhambane, Mozambique, HZM P.14052. A. detail of 3 lateral-most main paleae, B. detail of middle group palea; C. Red Sea, Holotype, NTM W.25602, detail of midline-most main and middle group paleae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Fig. 11 A</figureCitation>
, Red Sea; 
<figureCitation box="[556,655,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1838,1863]" captionTargetBox="[178,1419,386,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,373,1818]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 11. H. furfuricula sp. nov. A–B. Inhambane, Mozambique, HZM P.14052. A. detail of 3 lateral-most main paleae, B. detail of middle group palea; C. Red Sea, Holotype, NTM W.25602, detail of midline-most main and middle group paleae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[666,819,189,216]" name="Mozambique" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
); midline spines absent. Lateral and midline-most main paleae slightly more symmetrical, often with slightly involute shallow apices and 18–22 ribs (
<figureCitation box="[1211,1313,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1838,1863]" captionTargetBox="[178,1419,386,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,373,1818]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 11. H. furfuricula sp. nov. A–B. Inhambane, Mozambique, HZM P.14052. A. detail of 3 lateral-most main paleae, B. detail of middle group palea; C. Red Sea, Holotype, NTM W.25602, detail of midline-most main and middle group paleae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
). Main paleae relatively broad, with rounded brow, tiny, rounded apices, inner margin with minute serrations, convex margin with better-formed serration leading to apex. Notopodia with slender dorsal cirri, style extending just over half length of main paleae fan. Mid-body neurochaetae comprise: four long-bladed superior group; five mid superior; ~10 midgroup falcigers with slightly shorter, broader-blades with longer serrations; ~5 inferior group with shorter, slender blades. Total approximately 25/26. Ventral cirri finger- like, length to neuropodial tip.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="359" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,152,1007]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,441,467]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Watson Russell, C." box="[320,570,441,467]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" pagination="660 - 670" refId="ref19254" refString="Watson Russell, C. (1987) Chrysopetalidae. In: Bhaud, M. and Cazaux, C. Eds. Description and identification of polychaete larvae: their implications in current biological problems. Oceanis, 13, 660 - 670." type="journal article" year="1987">Watson Russell (1987)</bibRefCitation>
figured a small individual of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1985" box="[894,1009,441,467]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[894,1009,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Hyalopale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. from the Red Sea, possessing three pairs of eyes and typical lateral spines (
<bibRefCitation author="Watson Russell, C." box="[606,908,477,503]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" pagination="660 - 670" refId="ref19254" refString="Watson Russell, C. (1987) Chrysopetalidae. In: Bhaud, M. and Cazaux, C. Eds. Description and identification of polychaete larvae: their implications in current biological problems. Oceanis, 13, 660 - 670." type="journal article" year="1987">Watson Russell 1987: 668</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 27.4). 
<bibRefCitation author="Hartmann-Schroder, G." box="[1050,1354,477,504]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" pagination="69 - 125" refId="ref18022" refString="Hartmann-Schroder, G. (1960) Polychaeten aus dem Roten Meer. Kieler Meeresforschungen, 16, 69 - 125." type="journal article" year="1960">Hartmann-Schröder (1960)</bibRefCitation>
identified material from Ghardaga as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann-Schroder" authorityYear="1960" box="[508,766,513,539]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Paleanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="chrysolepis">
<emphasis box="[508,766,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Paleanotus chrysolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and Ben-Eliahu (1976) recorded 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann-Schroder" authorityYear="1960" box="[1142,1436,513,539]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Paleanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="chrysolepis">
<emphasis box="[1142,1267,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Paleanotus</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[1310,1436,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">chrysolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from intertidal sabellariid and vermetid reefs in the Gulf of Elat, with lateral ‘acicular notosetae’ (= lateral spines) and noted green material in the body. Re-examination of these specimens in addition to that from HZM museum collections identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann-Schroder" authorityYear="1960" box="[423,681,621,647]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Paleanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="chrysolepis">
<emphasis box="[423,681,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Paleanotus chrysolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Hartmann-Schröder from 
<collectingCountry box="[1013,1162,621,647]" name="Mozambique" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
, proved to be 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="furfuricula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Hyalopale furfuricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[278,367,657,683]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[278,367,657,683]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
The morphology of 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[596,839,657,683]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="furfuricula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[596,839,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Hyalopale furfuricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[846,935,657,683]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[846,935,657,683]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
main paleae from individuals of the Red Sea and 
<collectingCountry box="[200,346,693,719]" name="Mozambique" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
closely agrees especially in the characteristic main paleal shape with a distinctive rounded brow with tiny, almost involute apices plus the numbers of internal ribs and raised ribs with small denticles. These notochaetal characters distinguish 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[482,723,765,791]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="furfuricula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[482,723,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Hyalopale furfuricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[729,817,765,791]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[729,817,765,791]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from all other conspecifics, including those in adjoining regions: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[248,424,801,827]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bispinosa">
<emphasis box="[248,275,802,827]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">H.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[318,424,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">bispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Mediterranean Sea, to the north (cf 
<figureCitation box="[836,958,801,827]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[222,1365,166,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[222,1365,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Composite plate comparing notochaetal main paleae in Hyalopale species. A. Hyalopale bispinosa s.s. Florida, W. Atlantic; B. H. cf. bispinosa Crete, Mediterranean Sea; C. H. leslieae sp. nov. Florida Keys, W. Atlantic; D. H. furfuricula sp. nov. Mozambique, W. Indian Ocean; E. H. angeliensis sp. nov. Western Australia, E. Indian Ocean; F. H. zerofskii sp. nov. California, E. Pacific; G. H. sapphiriglancyorum sp. nov. E. Indonesia, W. Pacific. Note: correct number of raised and internal ribs figured." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442516/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Figs 1D, B</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[1022,1181,801,827]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="angeliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1022,1181,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">H. angeliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1188,1278,801,827]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1188,1278,801,827]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
to the east (cf 
<figureCitation box="[151,286,837,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[222,1365,166,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[222,1365,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Composite plate comparing notochaetal main paleae in Hyalopale species. A. Hyalopale bispinosa s.s. Florida, W. Atlantic; B. H. cf. bispinosa Crete, Mediterranean Sea; C. H. leslieae sp. nov. Florida Keys, W. Atlantic; D. H. furfuricula sp. nov. Mozambique, W. Indian Ocean; E. H. angeliensis sp. nov. Western Australia, E. Indian Ocean; F. H. zerofskii sp. nov. California, E. Pacific; G. H. sapphiriglancyorum sp. nov. E. Indonesia, W. Pacific. Note: correct number of raised and internal ribs figured." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3442516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3442516/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Figs 1 D, E</figureCitation>
). The mid-body neurochaetae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[663,907,837,863]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="furfuricula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[663,907,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Hyalopale furfuricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[916,1007,837,863]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[916,1007,837,863]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are shorter, with broader more robust blades, and distinct curved distal tips that are less attenuate, when compared to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[1133,1293,873,899]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="angeliensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1133,1293,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">H. angeliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1300,1389,873,899]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1300,1389,873,899]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse, 2019" authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,410,909,935]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="sapphiriglancyorum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,410,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">H. sapphiriglancyorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[417,506,909,935]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[417,506,909,935]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Unfortunately, no DNA sequences could be acquired for this new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="359" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,152,1007]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,945,971]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name, 
<emphasis box="[552,680,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson &amp; Tilic &amp; Rouse" authorityYear="2019" box="[552,676,945,971]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Hyalopale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="20" pageNumber="359" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="furfuricula">furfuricula</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
is a diminutive form of 
<emphasis box="[949,1014,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">furfur</emphasis>
from the Latin and refers to the many tiny raised denticles or flakes on the dorsal surface of the main paleae, which forms a 
<typeStatus box="[1113,1161,981,1007]" pageId="20" pageNumber="359">type</typeStatus>
of ‘scurf’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
